{"name":"Mathlib.Analysis.Calculus.Taylor","instances":[],"imports":["Init","Mathlib.Analysis.Calculus.IteratedDeriv","Mathlib.Analysis.Calculus.MeanValue","Mathlib.Data.Polynomial.Module"],"declarations":[{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Taylor.lean#L377-L390","name":"exists_taylor_mean_remainder_bound","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Taylor.html#exists_taylor_mean_remainder_bound","doc":"**Taylor's theorem** with a polynomial bound on the remainder\n\nWe assume that `f` is `n+1`-times continuously differentiable on the closed set `Icc a b`.\nThere exists a constant `C` such that for all `x ∈ Icc a b` the difference of `f` and its `n`-th\nTaylor polynomial can be estimated by `C * (x - a)^(n+1)`. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Taylor.lean#L334-L369","name":"taylor_mean_remainder_bound","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Taylor.html#taylor_mean_remainder_bound","doc":"**Taylor's theorem** with a polynomial bound on the remainder\n\nWe assume that `f` is `n+1`-times continuously differentiable on the closed set `Icc a b`.\nThe difference of `f` and its `n`-th Taylor polynomial can be estimated by\n`C * (x - a)^(n+1) / n!` where `C` is a bound for the `n+1`-th iterated derivative of `f`. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Taylor.lean#L313-L326","name":"taylor_mean_remainder_cauchy","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Taylor.html#taylor_mean_remainder_cauchy","doc":"**Taylor's theorem** with the Cauchy form of the remainder.\n\nWe assume that `f` is `n+1`-times continuously differentiable on the closed set `Icc x₀ x` and\n`n+1`-times differentiable on the open set `Ioo x₀ x`. Then there exists a `x' ∈ Ioo x₀ x` such that\n$$f(x) - (P_n f)(x₀, x) = \\frac{f^{(n+1)}(x') (x - x')^n (x-x₀)}{n!},$$\nwhere $P_n f$ denotes the Taylor polynomial of degree $n$ and $f^{(n+1)}$ is the $n+1$-th iterated\nderivative. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Taylor.lean#L272-L303","name":"taylor_mean_remainder_lagrange","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Taylor.html#taylor_mean_remainder_lagrange","doc":"**Taylor's theorem** with the Lagrange form of the remainder.\n\nWe assume that `f` is `n+1`-times continuously differentiable in the closed set `Icc x₀ x` and\n`n+1`-times differentiable on the open set `Ioo x₀ x`. Then there exists a `x' ∈ Ioo x₀ x` such that\n$$f(x) - (P_n f)(x₀, x) = \\frac{f^{(n+1)}(x') (x - x₀)^{n+1}}{(n+1)!},$$\nwhere $P_n f$ denotes the Taylor polynomial of degree $n$ and $f^{(n+1)}$ is the $n+1$-th iterated\nderivative. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Taylor.lean#L243-L262","name":"taylor_mean_remainder","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Taylor.html#taylor_mean_remainder","doc":"**Taylor's theorem** with the general mean value form of the remainder.\n\nWe assume that `f` is `n+1`-times continuously differentiable in the closed set `Icc x₀ x` and\n`n+1`-times differentiable on the open set `Ioo x₀ x`, and `g` is a differentiable function on\n`Ioo x₀ x` and continuous on `Icc x₀ x`. Then there exists a `x' ∈ Ioo x₀ x` such that\n$$f(x) - (P_n f)(x₀, x) = \\frac{(x - x')^n}{n!} \\frac{g(x) - g(x₀)}{g' x'},$$\nwhere $P_n f$ denotes the Taylor polynomial of degree $n$. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Taylor.lean#L224-L230","name":"has_deriv_within_taylorWithinEval_at_Icc","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Taylor.html#has_deriv_within_taylorWithinEval_at_Icc","doc":"Calculate the derivative of the Taylor polynomial with respect to `x₀`.\n\nVersion for closed intervals "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Taylor.lean#L210-L218","name":"taylorWithinEval_hasDerivAt_Ioo","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Taylor.html#taylorWithinEval_hasDerivAt_Ioo","doc":"Calculate the derivative of the Taylor polynomial with respect to `x₀`.\n\nVersion for open intervals "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Taylor.lean#L182-L204","name":"hasDerivWithinAt_taylorWithinEval","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Taylor.html#hasDerivWithinAt_taylorWithinEval","doc":"Calculate the derivative of the Taylor polynomial with respect to `x₀`.\n\nVersion for arbitrary sets "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Taylor.lean#L151-L176","name":"hasDerivWithinAt_taylor_coeff_within","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Taylor.html#hasDerivWithinAt_taylor_coeff_within","doc":""},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Taylor.lean#L143-L148","name":"monomial_has_deriv_aux","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Taylor.html#monomial_has_deriv_aux","doc":"Helper lemma for calculating the derivative of the monomial that appears in Taylor expansions."},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Taylor.lean#L128-L139","name":"continuousOn_taylorWithinEval","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Taylor.html#continuousOn_taylorWithinEval","doc":"If `f` is `n` times continuous differentiable on a set `s`, then the Taylor polynomial\n`taylorWithinEval f n s x₀ x` is continuous in `x₀`. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Taylor.lean#L117-L123","name":"taylor_within_apply","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Taylor.html#taylor_within_apply","doc":""},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Taylor.lean#L110-L114","name":"taylorWithinEval_self","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Taylor.html#taylorWithinEval_self","doc":"Evaluating the Taylor polynomial at `x = x₀` yields `f x`. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Taylor.lean#L100-L105","name":"taylor_within_zero_eval","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Taylor.html#taylor_within_zero_eval","doc":"The Taylor polynomial of order zero evaluates to `f x`. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Taylor.lean#L86-L95","name":"taylorWithinEval_succ","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Taylor.html#taylorWithinEval_succ","doc":""},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Taylor.lean#L77-L82","name":"taylorWithin_succ","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Taylor.html#taylorWithin_succ","doc":""},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Taylor.lean#L73-L74","name":"taylorWithinEval","kind":"def","docLink":"./Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Taylor.html#taylorWithinEval","doc":"The Taylor polynomial with derivatives inside of a set `s` considered as a function `ℝ → E`"},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Taylor.lean#L66-L69","name":"taylorWithin","kind":"def","docLink":"./Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Taylor.html#taylorWithin","doc":"The Taylor polynomial with derivatives inside of a set `s`.\n\nThe Taylor polynomial is given by\n$$∑_{k=0}^n \\frac{(x - x₀)^k}{k!} f^{(k)}(x₀),$$\nwhere $f^{(k)}(x₀)$ denotes the iterated derivative in the set `s`. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Taylor.lean#L57-L58","name":"taylorCoeffWithin","kind":"def","docLink":"./Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Taylor.html#taylorCoeffWithin","doc":"The `k`th coefficient of the Taylor polynomial. "}]}